NAT10 is the only enzyme in its family that as able to modify RNA, suggesting that ac4c is playing some unique role in gene expression but it is still mechansitically unknown how d/t limited methods to study it. So that’s why we (& a few other labs) are here to figure it out https://t.co/lg903B14sv

And b/c y’all are probably like wtf is ac4C & how is this relevant to cancer research?!? It is a RNA mod. generated by the disease-associated acetyltransferase NAT10 in humans. Overexpression of NAT10 has been linked in a subset of ovarian and colorectal cancers w/ bad prognosis

we found that humans & yeast have relatively low numbers of ac4C, whereas thermophiles have MASSIVE amounts (growth studies showed ⬆️ levels correlated w/ ⬆️ temp) which was then followed up w/ CryoEM and biophysical studies which provided insight into ac4Cs thermoadaptive roles.
It discusses the highly sensitive and specific methods we developed to map the RNA modification ac4C at a single nucleotide level in the RNA of yeast, human and a subset of thermophiles.
